/images/2022/08/yummy_recipes_up_full_screen_pwa_ios_hu_8ec7aae66b647c63.webp" type=image/webp><source media="(max-width: 834px)" srcset="/images/2022/08/yummy_recipes_up_full_screen_pwa_ios_hu_8de9be8cd7e40521.webp 2x,
/images/2022/08/yummy_recipes_up_full_screen_pwa_ios_hu_8de9be8cd7e40521.webp" type=image/webp><source media="(min-width: 835px)" srcset="/images/2022/08/yummy_recipes_up_full_screen_pwa_ios_hu_8de9be8cd7e40521.webp 2x,
/images/2022/08/yummy_recipes_up_full_screen_pwa_ios_hu_8de9be8cd7e40521.webp" type=image/webp><img src=/images/2022/08/yummy_recipes_up_full_screen_pwa_ios.jpg alt="PWA of Yummy Recipes in full screen on iOS" decoding=async width=887 height=1920 loading=lazy></picture></a></p><hr><p>In such simple way, we got implemented PWA into our website.</p><p>Without any external services, this can be implemented anywhere and developers with specific knowledge can use the full potential of service workers to push this even further.</p><p>What you may notice, some apps that are natively distributed through Google Play or Apple App Store are just a cover for PWA that is running in the background.</p><h2 id=optimising-resources>Optimising Resources <button type=button class=anchor data-title="Copy link to section: Optimising Resources" aria-label="Copy link to section: Optimising Resources" onclick='navigator.clipboard.writeText("https://dariusz.wieckiewicz.org/en/simple-implementation-pwa-webdev-mobile-first-design/#optimising-resources"),this.insertAdjacentHTML("afterend","<div class=link-copied>Link copied to clipboard</div>"),setTimeout(()=>{document.querySelectorAll(".link-copied").forEach(e=>e.remove())},3e3)'><svg height="1em" viewBox="0 96 960 960" width="1em"><path d="M450 776H280q-83 0-141.5-58.5T80 576t58.5-141.5T280 376h170v60H280q-58.333.0-99.167 40.765-40.833 40.764-40.833 99Q140 634 180.833 675q40.834 41 99.167 41h170v60zM325 606v-60h310v60H325zm185 170v-60h170q58.333.0 99.167-40.765 40.833-40.764 40.833-99Q820 518 779.167 477 738.333 436 680 436H510v-60h170q83 0 141.5 58.5T880 576t-58.5 141.5T680 776H510z"/></svg></button></h2><p><strong>There is one more thing before you finish.</strong></p><p>Once we have all worked nicely, we shall do one more thing to make this solution even better.</p><p>You need to remember that the manifest file will be loaded along with the website. Icons specified there also will be downloaded in the background.</p><p>We need to remember to optimise these resources.</p><p>Where most hosting companies will compress text, the graphic can be served as they are.</p><p>It&rsquo;s always good to optimise the icons that we generated as you will see that you may reduce their size dramatically.</p><p>It&rsquo;s better to serve 8kB favicon in 512x512 resolution than 60kB prior, especially when you will not see the difference on screen.</p><p>To do that, use one of the below websites:</p><ul><li><a href=https://compressor.io target=_blank rel=noopener>Compressor.io ‚Äì optimize and compress JPEG photos and PNG images</a></li><li><a href=https://imagecompressor.com target=_blank rel=noopener>Optimizilla ‚Äì Online Image –°ompressor</a></li><li><a href=https://squoosh.app target=_blank rel=noopener>Squoosh ‚Äì ultimate image optimizer</a></li></ul><div class=footnotes role=doc-endnotes><hr><ol><li id=fn:1><p>In my initial post and screenshots I referred to <code>?source=pwa</code> which I later changed to <code>?utm_source=pwa</code> to work better with <a href=/en/minimal-google-analytics-4-snippet/>Google Analytics in my minimal approach</a>.&#160;<a href=#fnref:1 class=footnote-backref role=doc-backlink>&#8617;&#xfe0e;</a></p></li></ol></div></div><footer class=article-footer aria-label="Post Tags"><strong aria-hidden=true>#</strong><a class=article-tag href=/en/tag/pwa/>pwa</a>
